---

Rub the @flank steak{1} with the @ras-el-hanout{1} spice and allow it to come to
room temperature.

> Our tip for this recipe is to take your meat out of the fridge at least 30
> mins before dinner which will allow you to cook it more evenly.

Add 500ml of water to a #pot{} with the @vegetable stock pot{1} and bring to the
boil. Peel and finely chop the @garlic{3%cloves}(peeled and finely chopped).
Finely chop the @spring onion{3}(finely chopped, including the green parts).
Peel the @carrot{2}(peeled) and slice into rounds as thinly as possible. Cut
the @red pepper{2}(cut in half, stems and seeds removed, sliced into thin strips).

Remove the #pot{} of stock from the heat and add the @couscous{some}. Cover and
set aside.

Meanwhile, put a #frying pan{} on medium heat and add @olive oil{2%tsp}. Once
hot, cook the garlic, spring onion, carrot, and red peppers for ~{4-5%minutes}
until softened slightly.

Season the steak on both sides with @salt{some} and @pepper{some}. Heat another
large frying pan over medium-high heat and add @olive oil{2%tsp}. When the pan
is hot, add the steak and sear on each side for ~{2-3%minutes} until nicely
coloured. Remove the steak from the pan and set aside.

> This cooks your steak medium-rare. If you like your steak well-done, cook it
> for an additional 3 mins on each side.

Whilst your steak is searing, roughly chop the @coriander{5}(roughly chopped)
and add three-quarters of it to the frying pan with the vegetables. Remove from
the heat, add the @baby spinach{4}(loosely packed) and @olive oil{4%tbsp}. Fold
everything together. When the couscous has fully soaked up all the water, add
that to the pan as well and stir to combine.

Grate in the zest of half the @lemon{1}(zested) and squeeze in 2 tbsp of its
juice.

Slice your steak, on the diagonal, into 1cm strips and serve with your couscous
and veg mix. Garnish with more fresh coriander.